# Desired Outcome

The Payments Domain should enable the organization to:

* Manage the complete lifecycle of client payments.
* Provide a single source of truth for payment information.
* Process payments consistently regardless of payment provider.
* Offer real-time visibility into payment status and history.
* Simplify integrations with external payment providers.
* Support reliable reconciliation and financial reporting.
* Enable traceability and auditability of all payment operations.
* Reduce operational complexity and manual intervention.
* Support future payment channels with minimal impact on existing systems.

---

# Success Measures

The effectiveness of the Payments Domain will be evaluated using measurable outcomes.

## Reliability

* ≥ 99.95% payment processing availability.
* ≥ 99.9% successful payment processing rate (excluding external provider failures).

## Performance

* Payment status updates available within 5 seconds.
* Payment initiation response time below 500 ms (excluding external provider latency).

## Operational Excellence

* 100% traceability for all payment transactions.
* Automated reconciliation for ≥ 95% of payments.
* Reduction in manual payment interventions.

## Business Outcomes

* Reduced payment-related incidents.
* Reduced client payment disputes.
* Faster issue resolution by support teams.
* Faster onboarding of new payment providers.

---

# Strategic Principles

The Payments Domain shall be guided by the following principles.

## Single Source of Truth

Payment information must have a single authoritative owner.

## Provider Agnostic Design

Business processes should not depend on specific payment providers.

## Auditability by Default

Every payment action must be traceable and historically preserved.

## Idempotency First

Operations must be safe to retry without creating duplicate payments.

## Event-Driven Communication

Payment state changes should be published as domain events to interested systems.

## Security by Design

Sensitive information must be protected throughout the entire payment lifecycle.

## Loose Coupling

External integrations must be isolated behind stable interfaces.

## Observability First

The system must expose sufficient logs, metrics, and traces to support operations.

## Evolutionary Architecture

The domain must be designed to support new payment methods, providers, and business requirements without major redesign.

---

# Non-Goals

The Payments Domain is intentionally not responsible for the following concerns.

## Customer Management

Creating or managing customer profiles is outside the scope of this domain.

## Invoice Generation

Invoice creation and lifecycle management belong to a separate Billing domain.

## Product Pricing

Price calculation and pricing strategies are not responsibilities of this domain.

## General Ledger Accounting

Accounting systems remain the source of truth for bookkeeping activities.

## Fraud Detection Engines

Fraud analysis may consume payment events but is not owned by this domain.

## Notification Delivery

Sending emails, SMS, or push notifications belongs to a dedicated Notifications domain.

## User Authentication

Identity management and access control belong to the Security or Identity domain.

## Reporting Platforms

Analytics and business intelligence systems consume payment data but are not part of this domain.
